Abstract:
As Human Digital Twins (HDTs) evolve into lifelong health companions,
role design has appeared as a strategy to structure multifaceted
interactions. However, empirical evidence of its impact on
user perception is scarce. Through an online survey (N=263), we
explored perceptions of 12 HDT roles within 3 groups: Self, Prediction
Maker, and Data Explorer. Participants evaluated each role
with preventive health scenarios across 5 perceptual dimensions
and completed 3 intra-group rankings. Our initial results suggest a
notable tension between the central "twinning" metaphor and the
significantly lower scores of the Self group across four dimensions.
Notably, Self-related roles did not elicit higher perceived emotional
support than others, and high perceptual scores did not consistently
translate into high rankings. These patterns suggest that emotional
support may be considered as a tradeoff dimension rather than a
primary expectation, inviting discussions on rigorous role selection
that goes beyond data mimicry in health technology design.
